D-19 -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAs seen in previous pandemics, girls and young women are particularly vulnerable as social issues such as homelessness, mental healthcare, access to education, and child labor are often exacerbated. The Girl in the Pandemic considers what academics, community activists, and those working in local, national, and global NGOs are learning about the lives of girls and young women during pandemics. Drawing from a range of responses during the pandemic including first person narratives, community ethnographies, and participatory action research, this collection offers a picture of how the COVID-19 pandemic played out in eight different countries.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xSocial aspects. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspects. 0aWomenxHealth and hygiene. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aApiot Okudi, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBednarczyk, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBootchadee, Suda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErulkar, Annabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaitán, Ana Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHailu, Eyasu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHair, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJommaroeng, Rapeepun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct